<span class="name"><a name="99921"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#4:&nbsp;<font color=black><b></b> Author:&nbsp;<b>Khyla The Apathetic</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=99921#99921"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Fri Mar 25, 2005 5:26 pm</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">i really cant beleive how underappreciated the color line is pre-55.
<br />

<br />
1st off, there's no reason to use 3 stuns to recharm a pet, you should either use the lvl 44 stun, or possibly the lvl 4 then 44 for a quicker inital cast.  Once the mob is stunned, take a step back, turn as you stop, and recharm.
<br />
But that's just the tip of the iceberg of what these spells can do.
<br />

<br />
Most of course know of the chain stun, (any combo of 3 of the lvl 4, 20, 44, and 52 will work, the 52's a bit more mana intensive, and the 4's a tad shakier in the rotation.  I personally like 20-44-52 with 4 as a backup for interrupts as a fast cast).  A little variation off this is the partial chain stun, most effective with knights, generally i used 20-44 stuns, it keeps the mob stunned for a larger portion of the time acting like another stacking slow for groups a bit light on healing, and of course, 20-44 are fairly low mana and have decent durations.
<br />

<br />
Everyone knows stuns have agro, what people forget is that if a mob is stunned, agro doesnt matter for a moment.  If i get agro or the cler gets agro, lvl 55 and under, most of the time unless the tank cant keep up with my stun agro, i find the best solution is to stun the mob to buy tank time to get control of it.  The also keeps the mob in 1 spot which is also needed in particular for wars to get agro easily.
<br />

<br />
Speaking of the benefit of keeping it in one spot, stuns can fill in as a makeshift snare, when a mob is running, jump infront of it and hit it with your stuns.  At 20% and less mobs generally dont last that long, so u dont need the mob motionless much longer than stun buys you.
<br />

<br />
And finally for what's prolly the most important and originally indended use of stuns, a stun in most situations will buy a few sec of calm to pre-target your mezes in a multi-pull(dont forget to target 2 mobs, once the 1st is locked down, toggle last target to your 2nd) and of course actually get off @ least 1 mez, and if you stun, run/turnstop*, mez, run/turnstop, mez, you can get 2 depending on terrain, mob reach, lag etc.  These are also, like targeted AE mezes very useful when so much dps comes into camp the tank wont last while you cast more than 1-2 spells to get all the damage off untill you start to solidify the situation. 
<br />

<br />
In gigantic pulls, i find the best technique is approx the following pattern, adjusted a bit for the size of the pull and the area.  Targeted AE mez on inc, stun agro that comes to you, run/turnstop, targeted AE stunned mobs,  etcetc untill only 1 mob is moving, Single mez 1 group of the mobs, and use targeted AE to hold groups untill the previous group of mobs has been killed, as with max mobs hit by targeted AEs, they actually become mana efficient(tho mana efficiency is not at all what they're about, another common misconception, its just a fringe benefit when youre holding a full targeted AE)
<br />

<br />
color stuns pre-55 are the glue that holds together all of the rest of the peices of our croud control.  If you havent figured out how to use them like that, i think you're missing a -lot- of what enc can do. And the same theories as used in the lower level stuff applies once you get your lvl 69 spells, tho due to how hard stuff hits, you have to slightly modify how to manage it(run/turnstops become -very- necissary, WoM on lvl 65 and unders can double the size of the train u can take with MM, im sure there are other high lvl pointers im forgetting)
<br />

<br />
*run/turnstop is running away from the mob while your spellgems are greyed.  once they've ungreyed, turn as you stop to halt your movenment instantly to be able to cast without interruption, and cast asap.  This buys you back the 2 sec while your spellgems are refreshing as the mob has to run 2 sec more to hit you again.  This trick is one of the harder one to get right consistantly, practice, practice, practice at it tho, it's crucial to doing broken things with an enc.  In fact, i might suggest doing it between every spell, wheather u need to or not, for a while to get the hang of how it feels and when you can start casting.  (ps, ive also found turning continuously for a sec while channeling the 1st round of hits can also help keep you from moving far enuf to interrupt your spell)</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
